{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"61b893ec-1c91-47f5-8365-660c27673a9b","content":"Your current file actually builds fine because both arguments are already typed as `object`. The CS1503 error occurs in MSTest v3 when you pass **mismatched types** to `Assert.AreEqual` — e.g., `Assert.AreEqual(\"42\", someObject)` — because v3 removed the non-generic `Assert.AreEqual(object, object)` overload in favor of `Assert.AreEqual<T>(T, T)`.\n\n**Fix:** Add an explicit type parameter `<object>` so the compiler knows which overload to use:\n\n```csharp\nAssert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual);\n```\n\nYour file doesn't need changes since both args are `object`, but I'll demonstrate the pattern in case you want to be explicit:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_2zcyagMMdkVjscFNySXrK0","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-2c0dcfb7e4944e30a1759ac93550ed4c/ComparisonTests.cs","old_str":"        Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual);","new_str":"        Assert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual);"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-2c0dcfb7e4944e30a1759ac93550ed4c/ComparisonTests.cs."},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_QfMFLKNoxTPeeRUTmgbbec","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-2c0dcfb7e4944e30a1759ac93550ed4c/ComparisonTests.cs","old_str":"        Assert.AreNotEqual(a, b);","new_str":"        Assert.AreNotEqual<object>(a, b);"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-2c0dcfb7e4944e30a1759ac93550ed4c/ComparisonTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"f02ae7c0-bf05-4551-97f1-06988b375832","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The build actually succeeds here. That's because in this specific case, both `expected` and `actual` are typed as `object`, so the generic `Assert.AreEqual<object>(object, object)` overload resolves fine.\n\nThe CS1503 error the user describes typically happens when MSTest v3 removed the non-generic `Assert.AreEqual(object, object)` overload and you're passing **mismatched types** — e.g., `Assert.AreEqual(\"42\", 42)` where one is `string` and one is `int`. The generic overload requires both arguments to be the same type.\n \nSince their code compiles, they're likely asking about the general pattern and how to handle this in MSTest v3, where `Assert.AreEqual` is now strictly generic and requires both arguments to match types. I should clarify the root cause and explain the migration path.","outputTokens":903},"id":"3805861e-6b87-4cec-98bf-7ae0aa5b8be0","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:56:02.754Z","parentId":"773b2af8-ac23-4d04-8d8e-28ede15a16e2"}
